From a reduplicated Proto-Indo-European imitative root; see also Irish uileliugh (“wail of lamentation”), Lithuanian uluti (“howl”), Sanskrit उलूलि (ulūli, “a howling, crying aloud”), Ancient Greek ὀλολύζω (ololúzō, “to cry aloud”), Old Armenian ողողանամ (ołołanam), ողողանիմ (ołołanim, “to wail, lament”), dialectal Armenian ուլուլալ (ululal, “to weep, cry, lament”), and Old English ūle (whence English owl).

Equivalent to con- +‎ nūbō (“I marry”) +‎ -ium. Per De Vaan, the cō-n- (found also in other words that are on the surface composed of con- + a stem starting with n-) has been explained as a development from previous *com-sn-.[1] Weiss reconstructs the word as going back to an original form *kon-snoubii̯om.[2] It is not simple to determine the usual length of the vowel in the second syllable using poetic evidence (see below). Long ū would be the regular outcome of a diphthong derived from the e- or o-grade of the Proto-Indo-European root (and would get analogical support from the long ū in nūbō); on the other hand, the related words prōnuba and innuba can be cited to support the possibility of a pronunciation with short /u/, which would come from the zero grade of the Proto-Indo-European root.

Uncertain. Perhaps related to Proto-Indo-European *bʰelǵʰ- (“to swell”). De Vaan, however, doubts the possibility of a semantic connection between the Latin term, meaning "to support," and the Proto-Indo-European term, meaning "to swell." The root *bʰelg- has been proposed based on a possible connection with Ancient Greek φᾰ́λᾰγξ (phắlănx), Old High German balko, and Icelandic bjálki, although De Vaan rejects such connections. Rix posits, albeit uncertainly, the root *bʰelḱ-, from which a form *bʰl̥ḱ-yé-ti may have emerged,[1] whence   fulciō.[2] However, the only other evidence for such a root is Ancient Greek φάλκης (phálkēs), which Beekes considers to be of Pre-Greek origin.[3]

vocabList.etym: From invidus (“envious”), from invideō (“envy, grudge”). Cognate with Proto-Slavic *zavistь (“envy”), Proto-Slavic *nenavistь (“hate”), Proto-Slavic *obvida (“resentment, indignation”).

vocabList.definition: the act of buying or purchasing, purchase
vocabList.etym: From the supine theme of emō (“to buy”) +‎ -tiō (action noun suffix).

vocabList.definition: a point connecting various parts of the body; joint, knot, knuckle.
vocabList.etym: Diminutive from artus (“joint; limbs”) +‎ -culus. In the grammatical sense, it is a semantic loan from Ancient Greek ἄρθρον (árthron).

vocabList.definition: of such size, of such measure
vocabList.etym: From tam (“so”) +‎ -tus (adjectival/adverbial ending); compare quantus, intus, subtus.
From in- (“not”) +‎ ultus (“avenged”).
Perfect passive participle of agnōscō.
From ex- +‎ probrum.
From Proto-Italic *sinō, from Proto-Indo-European *tḱi-né-ti, denominative present of the root *tḱey- (“to build, cultivate”).[1]
Perfect passive participle of laedō.
Perfect passive participle of permittō.
Possibly from circum- (“around”) +‎ -dō/-dere (“put”) subsequently remodelled to circum- +‎ dō/dare (“give”).[1]

vocabList.definition:
by what means, how
 by which means, by means of which, whereby
vocabList.etym: quā (“by what”) +‎ rē (“about, anent, with reference to”), ablative of rēs (“thing, matter, topic”).

Perfect passive participle of exerceō (“to occupy oneself, oversee; work at, practice, exercise”), from ex- (“out of”) +‎ arceō (“to ward off, protect, guard”), from Proto-Italic *arkeō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂orké-ye-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂erk- (“to protect, guard”).

From Proto-Italic *ū̆skʷe, from Proto-Indo-European *úds-kʷe, from *úd-s (“out, outward”, genitive) +‎ *-kʷe (“and”). Cognate with Sanskrit उच्चा (uccā́), Younger Avestan 𐬎𐬯𐬗𐬀 (usca, “up, out”), Russian вы- (vy-, “out from”), Proto-Germanic *ūt, English out.[1]
From patiens +‎ -ia.
From Proto-Indo-European *ksen-, extended from *kes- (“to scratch, itch”). Cognate with sentus, Ancient Greek ξαίνω (xaínō).
Derived from Proto-Indo-European *peth₂- (“to spread out”).

vocabList.definition: to look or gaze at, behold, watch, view
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *toweōr, from Proto-Indo-European *tewH- (“to look favorably, protect, observe”).[1]

vocabList.definition: one who lives near a place; a neighbor
vocabList.etym: From accolō (“to live near, to neighbor”) +‎ -a.

vocabList.definition: eternity, agelessness, timelessness (time as a single, unified, continuous and limitless entity; infinite time, time without end)
vocabList.etym: Earlier aevom, aivom, from Proto-Italic *aiwom (“period, age”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eyu- (“long time, lifetime”).
From prae- +‎ mittō (“send”).
From Proto-Italic *kolnis, from Proto-Indo-European *kl̥Hnís (“hill”), from the root *kelH- (“to rise; hill”). Cognate with Proto-Germanic *hulliz (English hill).[1]
id +‎ eō, i.e. "this for this".
From paveō +‎ -idus.
dē- +‎ sum
Perfect participle of polliceor (“I promise”).
From Proto-Italic *stolidos, from Proto-Indo-European *stel- (“to set, be stiff”) + -idus. Cognate with stultus, Ancient Greek στελεός (steleós).
From Proto-Italic *agros, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂éǵros. Cognates include Umbrian ager, South Picene akren, Ancient Greek ἀγρός (agrós), Sanskrit अज्र (ájra) and Old English æcer (English acre).
Perfect passive participle of fleō (“I weep, cry”).
.mw-parser-output .etytree{width:max-content;max-width:100%;overflow:hidden;box-sizing:border-box}

From Proto-Italic *tālis, from Proto-Indo-European *to- (“demonstrative stem”) and maybe *h₂el- (“to grow”) (cf. the sense of indolēs, from this root). Cognate with Ancient Greek τηλίκος (tēlíkos, “of such an age”), Welsh talu (“to pay”), Proto-Slavic *toliko (“this much”).[1]

vocabList.definition: The act of habituating; state of being habituated or accustomed, habituation.
vocabList.etym: From cōnsuēscō (“accustom, habituate; accustom oneself”) +‎ -tūdō, from con- (“with”) + suēscō (“become used or accustomed to; accustom, train”).
From in- (“not”) +‎ mītis (“mild, mellow, mature, ripe”).

vocabList.definition: seaweed; orchil, orchella weed, Roccella tinctoria
vocabList.etym: From Ancient Greek φῦκος (phûkos, “seaweed, orchil”).
From scrīptor (“writer, author”) +‎ -ium or equivalently, scrībō (“to write”) +‎ -tōrium (suffix forming nouns denoting places).
From Proto-Italic *nowos, from Proto-Indo-European *néwos. Cognates include Old English nīewe (English new), Ancient Greek νέος (néos), Proto-Slavic *novъ, and Sanskrit नव (náva).
From ob- (“before”) +‎ sedeō (“I sit”).
From sub- (“under”) +‎ sedeō (“sit”) +‎ -ium; see also subsīdō (“crouch down, settle down, squat”).
From pretium +‎ -ōsus.
From Ancient Greek ζώνη (zṓnē).

vocabList.definition: to say, speak, assert, say “yes”, affirm
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *agjō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁ǵyéti, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁eǵ- (“to say”).

vocabList.definition: that may or can be done or made
vocabList.etym: From faciō (“do, make”) +‎ -ilis.

vocabList.definition: to hold up or upright, uphold, support, sustain
vocabList.etym: From sub- +‎ teneō (“hold; restrain”). Compare, on composition and meaning, with the later formed subteneō (“to hold underneath”).
From strepō (“make a loud noise”) +‎ -tus.

From Proto-Indo-European *meh₃- (“to exert”) (though de Vaan reconstructs the Proto-Indo-European root as *melos (“trouble, obstacle”) instead).[1] Cognate with Ancient Greek μῶλος (môlos, “turmoil”) and German mühen (“to labor, toil”). See also Latin mōs.
From sulcus (“furrow, ditch, track”) +‎ -ō.

vocabList.definition: to dig out or up, excavate, mine
vocabList.etym: From ex- (“out of, from”) +‎ fodiō (“dig”).
From a Proto-Indo-European *Hrewp-(e)h₁-s (“cliff”),[2] from the root *Hrewp- (“break”).
From dē +‎ super.
From prae- (“before”) +‎ serō (“I join or bind together”) +‎ -tim (forms adverbs).

vocabList.definition: to leave, depart, abandon, retire (with ablative)
vocabList.etym: From dis- +‎ cēdō.

vocabList.definition: since, forasmuch, inasmuch as, now that
vocabList.etym: Univerbation of quom +‎ iam.
From Proto-Italic *ke-eteros, from *ke (“here”) +‎ *eteros (“other”).[1]

vocabList.definition: longing, desire, wish (especially for something once possessed)
vocabList.etym: From dēsīderō (“want, desire, wish for; miss, lack, need”) +‎ -ium.

vocabList.definition: to be accustomed, used to, in the habit of
vocabList.etym: PIE word*swé
For cunde, from a declined form of quī (“which, what, where”) and a demonstrative suffix *-de. See ubi for the loss of c and compare ali-cunde and sī-cunde.

From Proto-Italic *swordi- (“dirt”) or *swordo- (“dirty”)[1] + -ēs. Cognate with Proto-Germanic *swartaz (“black”), which could also go back to *sword-; within Latin, suāsum (“dirty gray color”) could be from the same root,[2] but this relationship is not certain since it is phonetically problematic.[1]

vocabList.definition: to lift up or raise (from underneath)
vocabList.etym: From sub- +‎ levo.

vocabList.definition: to be sad or mournful; mourn, grieve, lament
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *maizēō; further origin uncertain. Possibly related to miser (compare with misereō), and possibly related to Ancient Greek μῖσος (mîsos) by means of Proto-Indo-European *mēwdʰ- (“to complain, be emotional about”). De Vaan hesitantly suggests a connection to Proto-Indo-European *(s)meh₂- (“to beckon”).[1]
Present active participle of amō (“love”).
Back-formation from  nequeō, itself related to the irregular verb eō.
Perfect active participle of contestor.
From ex- (“out of”) +‎ veniō (“come”).
Perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *éy and *só. Compare ita and itidem.
From prō + dō (“to give”).
From dēlinquō (“fail, be wanting”).

vocabList.definition: to owe something, to be under obligation to and for something
vocabList.etym: Contraction of *dēhibeō, from dē- +‎ habeō (“have”), though "I hold away (from someone)".[1] See the same contraction in dēbilis. Compare the later formed dēhabeō.
Present participle of cū̆nctor.
From dē (“from, away or down from”) + decus (“glory, honor, dignity”).
Perfect passive participle of permoveō.

From Proto-Italic *rē(z)mos, from a Proto-Indo-European root *h₁reh₁- shared with Ancient Greek ἐρετμός (eretmós, “oar”), ἐρέτης (erétēs, “rower”), τριήρης (triḗrēs, “trireme”), and possibly English oar.

vocabList.definition: to pay attention, attend, focus, concentrate, give heed to, consider, regard, observe
vocabList.etym: From animus +‎ advertō.

vocabList.definition: desire, longing, especially amorous desire, eagerness
vocabList.etym: From cupiō (“to desire”) +‎ -īdō.

vocabList.definition: to beg, to demand, to request, to desire
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *porskō (“to ask for; request; demand”), from Proto-Indo-European *pr̥(ḱ)sḱéti (“to keep asking; to question”), from *preḱ- (“to ask; to ask for”) +‎ *-sḱéti (“imperfective suffix”). Latin -ēscō (inchoative suffix) derives separately from this ending.

vocabList.definition: which is to be examined, contemplated, observed
vocabList.etym: Future passive participle of īnspiciō.
See vās. The word is pre-Classical. In Classical Latin it is only used in the plural.

vocabList.definition:
to take away, take off, bear away, bear off, carry off, remove, withdraw
  to bear or carry away, sweep away by wings, the winds, waves, or any other quick motion
vocabList.etym: From au- (“from, away, off”) +‎ ferō (“to bear, carry, bring”). Whether the prefix au- is identical to ab- is the source of much controversy; see au- for more.
From Proto-Italic *kensēō, from earlier *kensējō, from Proto-Indo-European *ḱenséh₁-ye-ti, from *ḱens- (“to announce”). Cognate with Sanskrit शंसति (śáṃsati, “to declare”), Proto-Iranian *cánhati.

vocabList.definition: which is to be created, which is to be made, which is to be produced
vocabList.etym: Future passive participle (gerundive) of creō (“create”).
From adeō (“approach, attend, undertake”) +‎ -tus (action noun forming suffix).
From et (“even”) +‎ sī (“if”).
From hiems (“winter, rainy season”).
From exig(ō) (“to demand”) +‎ -uus.
From arbiter +‎ -ō.

vocabList.definition: to move away, leave, withdraw, break away
vocabList.etym: From de- +‎ facio.
From per- (“through”) +‎ -dō (“put”).
Perfect passive participle of spoliō.
Disputed.
From iste + -ce.
From ob- +‎ sacrō (“consecrate”).

vocabList.definition: to look back, around, continuously or intently
vocabList.etym: From re- +‎ spectō, cf. respectus.

vocabList.definition: to spread, stretch out, spread out
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *stornō, from Proto-Indo-European *str̥-n-h₃-, n-infix present of the root *sterh₃- (“to spread, extend”).[1] Cognate with Sanskrit आस्तॄ (āstṝ, “spread”), Avestan 𐬯𐬙𐬆𐬭𐬆𐬥𐬁𐬌𐬙𐬌 (stərənāiti, “spread, extend”), Ancient Greek στόρνυμι (stórnumi, “scatter”), στρατός (stratós, “army, people, body of men”), Old Church Slavonic прострѣти (prostrěti, “stretch, expand”), просторъ (prostorŭ, “spaciousness”), Old English strewian (English strew), Old Norse strá.

vocabList.definition: to fill up, fill full, fill out; make up, complete
vocabList.etym: From con- +‎ pleō.

From cāssus with regular degemination after a long vowel, for cadō (“to fall, happen”) +‎ -tus (“action noun suffix”), from Proto-Italic *kadō, Proto-Indo-European *ḱh₂d- (“to fall”). The grammatical sense is a semantic loan from Ancient Greek πτῶσις (ptôsis) (whence also calqued Old Church Slavonic падежь (padežĭ) (Russian паде́ж (padéž)), German Fall).
Perfect passive participle of corripiō (“to seize”).

Unknown.[1] De Vaan is skeptical of the proposal that it originally referred to the hair on an animal's back and was derived from a Proto-Indo-European *(s)ter- (“to be stiff”)[1] (compare *tr̥nós, *sterbʰ-). It has been speculated to be connected to one or more of Ancient Greek τράχηλος (trákhēlos, “neck”), Ancient Greek τρέχω (trékhō), or Latin trahō, with a debated connection to the root of English drag, draw.

From Proto-Italic *wetos (“year”), from Proto-Indo-European *wétos (“year”). The Latin underwent semantic shift "year" > "having accumulated (many) years" > "aged, old", with the Latin term for year being annus, from a different root.[1]
From nec + opinatus.
From the ablative of fors (“chance, luck”).
From Proto-Italic *ke-eteros, from *ke (“here”) +‎ *eteros (“other”).[1]
From Proto-Italic *dūm (adverb), from *dweh₂- (“long”) +‎ *-m (adverbial suffix). Compare dūdum.[1]

From poscō (“beg, demand, request, desire”) from Proto-Italic *porskō (“to ask for; request; demand”), from Proto-Indo-European *pr̥(ḱ)sḱéti (“to keep asking; to question”), from *preḱ- (“to ask; to ask for”) +‎ *-sḱéti (“imperfective suffix”).
From mora (“delay”) +‎ -or (deponent verb-forming suffix).
From ne (“not”) + usquam (“anywhere”).

vocabList.definition: put in motion, moved, stirred, shaken; quick, swift, rapid; having been moved
vocabList.etym: Perfect passive participle of cieō (“put in motion”).

vocabList.definition: to have an aversion towards, to hate, dislike
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Indo-European *h₃e-h₃ód-e ~ h₃e-h₃d-ḗr, reduplicated perfect from the root *h₃ed- (“to hate; to start hating?”).[1][2]
From puer (“male child, boy”) +‎ -itia.

vocabList.definition: to kill, murder (especially without physical wounding such as by poison or hunger)
vocabList.etym: From nec- +‎ -ō (denominative verb suffix), from Proto-Indo-European *neḱ- (“perish, disappear”).

vocabList.definition: to press down upon; to suppress
vocabList.etym: From ob- +‎ premō (“press”).
Frequentative of horior. See -tō.

vocabList.definition: to remember, recollect, recall, call to mind, think of
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *memonai, from Proto-Indo-European *memóne (“to remember”), perfect of the root *men- (“to think”). Compare mēns (“mind”).

vocabList.definition: to wander through; to rove about
vocabList.etym: From per- +‎ vagor.

vocabList.definition: to lay waste, ravage or devastate, destroy or ruin
vocabList.etym: From populus (“human, community, people”). According to De Vaan, the meaning developed from an earlier sense "to have an army pass through".[1]

vocabList.definition: to go before, precede (walk on ahead)
vocabList.etym: From ante- +‎ eō. Forms in antid- are part of the same analogy as redeō, antideā, to avoid hiatus.

From earlier *well, from *wels, from *welsi (“you wish”), thus originally the second-person singular present active indicative form of volō (“I will, I wish”). The semantic development may have been helped by the fortuitous similarity to -ve.

Perhaps from Proto-Italic *kengō, from a Proto-Indo-European *kenk- (“to gird, tie”). Possibly related to Lithuanian kinkýti (“to bridle horses”) and Sanskrit कञ्च् (kañc, “to bind”), कञ्चुक (kañcuka, “armor”); however, these terms present phonetic problems regarding their cognacy.[1]
From Proto-Italic *eno (“that one”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁enos (“that”), the same source of nam, nē (“truly”), Ancient Greek νή (nḗ), ναί (naí).

vocabList.definition: surrounded, enclosed, having been fenced in.
vocabList.etym: Perfect passive participle of saepiō (“surround, enclose”).

vocabList.definition: delay, or any duration of time.
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *morā, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)mer- (“to fall into thinking, remember, care for”).
Perfect passive participle of pervagor.

vocabList.definition: (among nations, states, or rulers) treaty, compact, alliance, truce, league
vocabList.etym: Inherited from Proto-Italic *feiðos (“faithful”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeydʰ-os, from *bʰeydʰ- (“to trust”). Same root as fīdō, fidēs, fīdus, and Proto-Germanic *bīdaną. Perhaps a corruption from an o-stem.[1]
From com- (“together”) +‎ -es (“-faring”).

vocabList.definition: to lay straight; arrange in lines (especially in military contexts)
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *dwizregō. Equivalent to dis- +‎ regō (“I rule, govern”).
From Proto-Indo-European *Hrew- (“to tear up, dig up”). Related to rudus.
According to Michiel De Vaan's Etymological Dictionary of Latin and the other Italic Languages (2008), probably from the same root as pariō.

vocabList.definition: to have respect for, revere, stand in awe
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *werēōr, from Proto-Indo-European *wer- (“to cover, heed, notice”). Cognate with Ancient Greek ὁράω (horáō, “see”) < ϝοράω (woráō), and English aware [1] and wary.
From Proto-Italic *staēō, from earlier *staējō, from Proto-Indo-European *sth₂éh₁yeti, stative verb from *steh₂-.
Earlier *tlātus, from Proto-Italic *tlātos, from Proto-Indo-European *tl̥h₂tós, from the root *telh₂-.

vocabList.definition: each one, each person, each individual
vocabList.etym: From quis +‎ -que (“each”). Compare to quoque and quisquam, and a parallel development in Gothic 𐍈𐌰𐌶𐌿𐌷 (ƕazuh).
From cārus (“dear, expensive”) +‎ -tās.
From quī +‎ vīs.

Apparently from Proto-Indo-European *ḱreh₁- (“to grow”), the same root of Latin crēscō,  +‎ *-rós, but the /b/ lacks explanation. Perhaps from Proto-Italic *krēzros, from Proto-Indo-European *ḱreh₁-s-ro- (compare crābrō < *krāzrō for the phonetics), or from a suffixed verb *ḱreh₁-dʰh₁- (compare ruber < *ruðros).
Apocopated form of neque.
From Proto-Italic *pākslā, from Proto-Indo-European *pak-slo-, from *peh₂ǵ- (“to attach, fasten”). See pangō, pāgus, pacīscor, pāx, pāgina.[1]

vocabList.definition: to cry out, shout, scream, exclaim
vocabList.etym: From vōcifer.
From older seive, from sei (“if”) +‎ -ve (“or”). Equivalent to sī (“if”) +‎ -ve (“or”). Collateral form seu by apocope.

vocabList.definition: to keep busy, keep at work, drive on; occupy, practise, employ, exercise (something in a form of action)
vocabList.etym: From ex- (“out of, from”) +‎ arceō (“enclose; ward off”).
Apocope of sīve.
Possibly for *provillium, *produillium from bellum, duellum.

vocabList.definition: at length, at last, finally, eventually
vocabList.etym: From tam (“so”) +‎ -dem (“new interpreted particle from īdem”). Compare with its earlier doublet: tamen. Both with original meaning supposedly "so(much)ever".

vocabList.definition: to be astonished at, marvel at, admire, be amazed at, wonder at
vocabList.etym: From mīrus (“remarkable, astonishing”), from Proto-Italic *smeiros, from Proto-Indo-European *sméyros (“laughing, smiling”), from *(s)mey- (“to laugh, to be glad”).[1]
From ante (“before”) + ea (“these things”).

vocabList.definition: to delight, charm, please (+ accusative the person, who is delighted)
vocabList.etym: Frequentative of dēliciō, or else from dē- +‎ lactō.
Probably from ut +‎ quam, with intermediate Proto-Italic *utVs (“so that, as”) plus indefinitizing quam. Compare uspiam.

vocabList.definition: pleasantness, pleasurableness, delightfulness, loveliness, agreeableness, charm
vocabList.etym: From amoenus (“pleasant, delightful, lovely”) +‎ -tās.

From Proto-Italic *rāros, probably from Proto-Indo-European *h₁r̥h₁rós, from *h₁reh₁- (“to separate”) (though Schrijver and de Vaan are skeptical). Cognate with Ancient Greek ἐρῆμος (erêmos, “lonely”).

vocabList.definition: without a doubt, no doubt, of course
vocabList.etym: Univerbation of nī, mīrum ("if not, that would be odd").
Perfect active participle of sequor (“to follow”) (for expected *sectus, proven by sector, possibly after volūtus, solūtus etc.).

vocabList.definition: scarcely, hardly, by no means, not, not at all
vocabList.etym: Maybe from the same Proto-Indo-European root as Cornish gow (“lie”).[1]

vocabList.definition: to go, move, proceed, go along, move along
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *kezdō, further derivation disputed.
quot +‎ -iēns
Reduplication of  quis.
For *propiter, from prope. Compare with inter (“between”) and subter (“beneath”).

vocabList.definition: to perish, pass away, die, be ruined
vocabList.etym: From per- (“through”) +‎ eō (“go”).
From Proto-Italic *klaudō, from Proto-Indo-European *kleh₂u-de-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *kleh₂u- (“key, hook, nail”).

Derived from Proto-Italic *domaō, from earlier *domajō, from Proto-Indo-European *démh₂-e-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *demh₂- (“to domesticate, tame”). One of those Latin verbs (as iuvō) only classed in the 1st conj. by the action of sound laws (Can this(+) etymology be sourced?).

From Proto-Italic *auzjō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ews-ye-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ews- (“to scoop, draw water”), whence also Proto-Germanic *ausaną (“to scoop, draw water”) and Ancient Greek αὔω (aúō, “to light a fire”), with the /h-/ likely inserted by hypercorrection.[1]
From sōlor (“to comfort, console, solace”) +‎ -āx +‎ -ium.
From pateō (“be open”) + faciō (“make, construct”).
From in + ops (“power, ability, wealth”).

vocabList.definition: that which flees, has fled, fugitive
vocabList.etym: From prōfugiō (“I flee, run away or escape”).
From Proto-Italic *kanō, from Proto-Indo-European *kh₂n-é-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *keh₂n- (“to sing”). Compare carmen (“song”) (< *kanmen).

vocabList.definition: even as, as, just as, like, as if
vocabList.etym: vel +‎ ut
From Proto-Italic *flēō, from earlier *flējō, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰleh₁- (“to bleat, cry”).[1]

vocabList.definition: to groan, moan or sigh (at or over)
vocabList.etym: From in- +‎ gemō.
From sīc (“thus, so”) +‎ ut (“how, as”).
From pateō (“to be open”) +‎ -ulus.
From sēmi- +‎ ustus. For the contraction of /i/ and /u/ through internal sandhi as well as etymologically, compare sēmustulō.
From dēlu(ō) (“to cleanse”) +‎ -brum, from de- + lavō (“I wash”).

Perhaps from praes (“surety, bondsman”) +‎ -ium.
Others refer it to praehendō.
For quid (“what, why, well!”, interjection) +‎ -pe, the same corroborating particle seen in nempe; see also quispiam.
Perfect passive participle of prōruō.
From pro- +‎ ruo.
im- +‎ mēnsus.[1]

vocabList.definition: to go or march on; to advance
vocabList.etym: Frequentative verb from gradior.

From Proto-Indo-European *sterh₃-, the root of sternō (“I spread, bestrew, scatter, fell”), with a *-g- extension. Cognate with Ancient Greek στόρνυμι (stórnumi, “scatter”), στρατός (stratós, “army, people, body of men”), Old English strewian (English strew).

vocabList.definition: some sort of snare or trap
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *tenos, from Proto-Indo-European *ténos, from *ten- (“to stretch, draw”). Cognate with  Sanskrit तनस् (tánas), Ancient Greek *τένος (*ténos) (attested in ἀτενής (atenḗs)), also with German Dohne which has the same meaning. More at teneō (“hold, grasp”).[1]
Unknown.[1][2] Maybe from earlier *verstīgium, from verrō (“to sweep”).[3] Or, possibly from vē- +‎ *stīgō, from Proto-Indo-European *stéygʰeti (“to walk”).
From lacer.

vocabList.definition: Covered, concealed, hidden; having been covered, hidden or concealed
vocabList.etym: Perfect passive participle of tegō (“cover; shelter”).
From sē +‎ -cum (“with”).

From in- (“within”) +‎ signum (“a sign, an emblem”) +‎ -is (suffix forming an adjective); so formed because the subject qualified by this adjective has been revealed, specifically by means of a sign, to be exceptional relative to ordinary examples of its kind.
From quis +‎ -dam (indefinite adverbial suffix). Compare quondam (“at one time”).

vocabList.definition: long, a long while, a while, for long, for a long time
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *djous, from Proto-Indo-European *dyéw(i) (“during the day”), locative case of *dyḗws, with d possibly imported from diēs. Cognate with Old Armenian տիւ (tiw), Sanskrit दिवा (divā, “by day”).
From ob- (“to, against”) +‎ iūrgō (“dispute, chide”).
From Proto-Italic *plousisemos. Suppletive superlative of multus (“many”).

vocabList.definition: to esteem, prize, love, have regard, to delight in (something)
vocabList.etym: From dis- (“apart, asunder”) +‎ legō (“to choose, to take”), or from dis- (“utterly, exceedingly”) +‎ Proto-Italic *legō (“to care”).
From Proto-Italic *kʷoizā, from Proto-Indo-European *kʷeys- (“to heed”).

vocabList.definition: to join, unite, fasten, yoke, harness, attach; esp. of the hand: to clasp, join
bad reputation or repute, ill fame, dishonor, disgrace, infamy, reproach
vocabList.etym: From īnfāmis (“infamous”), from in- (“not”) + fāma (“fame, renown”).

vocabList.definition: to use, make use of, employ
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *oitōr (with ūsus for *issus after ūtor), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *h₃eyt- (“to take along, fetch”). Compare the future tense οἴσω (oísō) of Ancient Greek φέρω (phérō, “carry”).
From Proto-Indo-European *sm̥meh₁lom (“one time”), from *sem- (“together”) and *meh₁-lo- (“measure, time”), from *meh₁- (“to measure”). See each for cognate words.

Most likely from Proto-Italic *pro- + *prijos (“own, dear”), from Proto-Indo-European *priHós (“dear”). Since pro- can hardly be explained as a nominal prefix, Forssman (2004) explains it as having been extended to the adjective from the verb propriāre, once-attested as propriāssit. Cognate to Sanskrit प्रिय (priyá, “dear”), Russian прия́тель (prijátelʹ, “buddy, mate”) and Russian прия́тный (prijátnyj, “pleasant”), Welsh rhydd (“free”), English free.[1]
A substantivisation of the masculine plural forms of the adjective plērusque.
From valeō (“I am strong, I am healthy, I am worth”) +‎ -idus.
Univerbation of nōn (“not”) +‎ dum (“while, as, as long as”).
Perfect passive participle of adigō (“drive, hurl”).
From Proto-Italic *plēros, from Proto-Indo-European *pleh₁-. Compare Ancient Greek πλήρης (plḗrēs).

vocabList.definition: quarrel, brawl, dispute, contest, strife, contention
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Indo-European *h₁riḱ-s-eh₂, whence also Ancient Greek ἐρείκω (ereíkō, “to rend, bruise, pound”).[1]

vocabList.definition: to bind together, connect, join, unite, yoke together, juxtapose
vocabList.etym: From con- (“with, together”) +‎ iungō (“to join, unite, connect”).
For *provorsus, from prō + versus, vorsus (“turned”).

vocabList.definition: which is to be united, made friendly, reconciled, won over
vocabList.etym: Future passive participle (gerundive) of conciliō
Present active participle of ineō (“enter”)

Perfect passive participle of exerceō (“to occupy oneself, oversee; work at, practice, exercise”), from ex- (“out of”) +‎ arceō (“to ward off, protect, guard”), from Proto-Italic *arkeō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂orké-ye-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂erk- (“to protect, guard”).

vocabList.definition: to lay, set, put or place aside or away; deposit
to finish play, cease to sport
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *eksloidō. By surface analysis, ē (“out of”) + lūdō (“play; trick”).
From Proto-Italic *esto, from Proto-Indo-European *só, with only the second part declining.
Perfect passive participle of effrēnō.
From praeses (“guardian, defender”) +‎ -ium or praesideō (“to guard, defend”) +‎ -ium.
Perfect passive participle of concurrō.
From fūr (“thief”) +‎ -ō.
Unknown; possibly related to Hittite 𒅕𒄩𒀸 (er-ḫa-aš /⁠erḫaš⁠/, “line, boundary”), Latvian āra, perhaps all from Proto-Indo-European *h₁erh₂- (“border, line”).[1][2]
Perfect passive participle of cōnstringō.

vocabList.definition: manner (of behaving), way (of behaving); behavior, conduct
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *mōs, a root noun interpreted as an s-stem noun, of uncertain origin. Generally believed to derive from Proto-Indo-European *moh₁-, *meh₁- (“to intend or be intent upon, to be of strong will”) (though the more common meaning of “to measure” may be the original, with “to intend” as a semantic extension),[1] whence Ancient Greek μαίομαι (maíomai, “to strive”) and perhaps Ancient Greek Μοῦσᾰ (Moûsă, “Muse”), and also English mood.

vocabList.definition: eager, desirous, passionate, fond (+ genitive or + in ablative)
vocabList.etym: From cupiō +‎ -idus.
Future participle of conciliō.
From perfidus +‎ -ia.

vocabList.definition: pity, compassion, mercy, lovingkindness, tenderness, heartedness
vocabList.etym: From misericors (“pitiful, compassionate, merciful”) +‎ -ia.

vocabList.definition: to uphold, support, prop or sustain, maintain
vocabList.etym: Frequentative verb of sustineō.
From Proto-Indo-European *nū (“now”).
From libēns (“willing, cheerful”) +‎ -ter.

vocabList.definition: to orate, deliver a speech publicly
vocabList.etym: The etymology of this word hinges on whether Oscan urust should be accepted as cognate:

vocabList.definition: to waver (in opinion), be uncertain, doubt, question, be in doubt

vocabList.etym: Future passive participle of perspiciō.
Perfect passive participle of audeō.
Borrowed from Ancient Greek χάρτης (khártēs, “paper”), with a change to the feminine gender.

vocabList.definition: to unfold, unfurl, uncoil, loosen, undo
vocabList.etym: From ex- +‎ plicō (“I fold”).

vocabList.definition: by chance, by accident, at random
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *temezi (“in darkness, blindly”), a fossilised locative form of Proto-Indo-European *témHos (“darkness”), from *temH- (“dark”). Cognate with Sanskrit तमस् (támas), Persian تم (tam), Latin tenebrae (“darkness”).[1]
From cōps +‎ -ia.
Perfect passive participle of trāiciō.
From circus (“circle, ring”) +‎ -ter.
Supposed to have been earlier *priuscus, from prior, q.v. Equivalent to prius +‎ -cus; ultimately composed of Proto-Indo-European *pre- + *-yōs + *-kos.[1] Possibly cognate to English fresh.
From con- +‎ emō. Compare with its contracted form cōmō.

From Proto-Italic *tonaō, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)tenh₂- (“to thunder”), replacing the likely earlier form tonere (“thunder”). One of few Latin verbs (as domō) only classed in the 1st conj. by the action of sound laws.  Cognate with Old Norse Þórr (“Thor”), English thunder.

vocabList.definition: to place, put, set in order, assign
vocabList.etym: con- +‎ locō (“put, place, set”)
Back-formation from  nequeō, itself related to the irregular verb eō.
Perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *(s)teg- (“beam, stake”) (whence also tignum).
From ad- (“toward, to”) +‎ agō (“do, make”).

vocabList.definition: to place in command, put in charge
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *praifakjō. Equivalent to prae- (“before”) +‎ faciō (“do, make”).
From Proto-Italic *relikuwos, from Proto-Indo-European *leykʷ-. Related to Latin linquō, itself derived from Proto-Italic *linkʷō.
Perfect participle of nancīscor
From mīrus +‎ -ficus.

vocabList.definition: to say, speak, assert, say “yes”, affirm
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *agjō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁ǵyéti, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁eǵ- (“to say”).
Present active participle of tollō (“lift up; remove”).
See also ligō, vinciō for other examples of words meaning to bind or turn, having derivatives with the sense of obliging.
From Proto-Italic *nepōts, from Proto-Indo-European *népōts.
From Proto-Italic *kʷot, from Proto-Indo-European *kʷóti, adverb from *kʷos, *kʷís. Cognate with Ancient Greek πόσος (pósos) and Sanskrit कति (kati).
Adverbial accusative of  nimius (“too great, excessive”).
For *cuter, from Proto-Indo-European *kʷóteros, from *kʷos (“which”), ultimately from *kʷ-. Cognate with Ancient Greek πότερος (póteros, “which of the two”) and English whether.
From *seksnos, equivalent to sex +‎ -nus.

vocabList.definition: severe, serious, strict, stern, stringent, austere, harsh,  grave
vocabList.etym: Other etymologists, such as Meiser, posit this word to be from se- + verus, but De Vaan notes a heavy semantic mismatch.[1]

vocabList.definition: to sew together, sew up, stitch, join
vocabList.etym: From con- +‎ suō.
From earlier paullus, likely from Proto-Italic *paukslos, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂w- (“few, small”) + *-ko- + *-slom, the first two elements also giving Latin paucus (“few”).[1]

vocabList.definition: to throw or bring together, unite, connect
vocabList.etym: From con- (“with, together”) +‎ iaciō (“throw, hurl”).
Perfect passive participle of perterreō.
From alacer (“brisk”) +‎ -tās (“-ity”).
Future passive participle (gerundive) of dēsiliō
From earlier vorsus, from Proto-Italic *worssos, perfect passive participle of vertō (“to turn”).

vocabList.definition: Thoroughly moved, agitated or disturbed; restless, unceasing.
vocabList.etym: From sollus (“whole, entire”) + cieō (“move, stir, shake”).

vocabList.definition: permitted, allowed, suffered, having been permitted
vocabList.etym: Perfect passive participle of sinō (“put, lay, set down; usually let, suffer, permit”).

vocabList.definition: without, lacking in, deprived (+ genitive or ablative)
vocabList.etym: From ex + pars (“part”).

vocabList.definition: A judicial decision, verdict, or judgment.
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *kreimən, from Proto-Indo-European *kréymn̥, from *krey- (“sieve”) + *-mn̥, equivalent to cernō (“sieve”) +‎ -men (noun-forming suffix). Compare also Ancient Greek κρῖμα (krîma).[1]
Probably the post-tonic development of *agetor 'it is done' (> agitur) after e.g. quid.
From Proto-Italic *perifakjō. Equivalent to per- (“through, along; during”) +‎ faciō (“do, make”).

vocabList.definition: to die, be slain, fall (in battle), perish
vocabList.etym: Cognate with Ancient Greek βροτός (brotós, “mortal”), Proto-Germanic *murþaz, Proto-Celtic *marwos, Lithuanian mirti (“death”), Sanskrit मृत्यु (mṛtyú, “death”), Proto-Slavic *merti. Related to mors (“death”).
From sē- (“without”) +‎ cūra (“care”); see cure. Similar to Latin sine cūrā (“without care, carefree”), which led to English sinecure.

vocabList.definition: to be astonished at, marvel at, admire, be amazed at, wonder at
vocabList.etym: From mīrus (“remarkable, astonishing”), from Proto-Italic *smeiros, from Proto-Indo-European *sméyros (“laughing, smiling”), from *(s)mey- (“to laugh, to be glad”).[1]

vocabList.definition: to be stunned, stiffened or benumbed, stop, hesitate
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Indo-European *(s)tup-éh₁-ye-ti (literally “to be struck”), from *(s)tewp- (“to push, hit”) +‎ *-éh₁yeti (stative verb suffix).[1]
From per- (prefix meaning ‘by means of; through’) +‎ turbō (“to agitate, disturb, unsettle, perturb; to upset”).

vocabList.definition: to run into; to go to meet
vocabList.etym: Derived from ob- (“towards; against”) +‎ currō (“I run”).
From Proto-Italic *waðom, from Proto-Indo-European *wh₂dʰóm (compare Proto-Germanic *wadą) < *weh₂dʰ-, same source as vādō. Cognate with Old English wadan (English wade).[1]
The derivatives of dō are not always easy to distinguish from those of -dō (“put”) < *dʰeh₁-.
From prō- +‎ sequor (“follow”).
currō +‎ -sus (action noun)
From unattested *prīs, zero-grade-suffix variant of prius (compare magis, maius), and -tinus. First element is from Proto-Indo-European *per; second element from Proto-Indo-European *ten-.
From circum- +‎ sistō.
From Proto-Italic *fugā, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰugéh₂. Cognate to Ancient Greek φυγή (phugḗ).
Future active participle of dō.
Perfect participle of queror

vocabList.definition: to send for, call, invite, summon, fetch
vocabList.etym: From accedō +‎ -tō, with ar- for ad- (as in arbiter).

Uncertain. Maybe from Proto-Indo-European *ḱwes- (“to puff, sigh”), in which case it is cognate with English quarrel, wheeze, Icelandic hvæsa (“to hiss”) and Sanskrit श्वसिति (śvasiti, “to puff”), Pashto ساه (sāh, “breath, blow, puff, soul, spirit, essence”), Baluchi ساہ (sáh, “breath, blow, essence”).[1]
ali- (“some”) +‎ quotiēns (“how many times”).

vocabList.definition: carried or conducted forward or along
vocabList.etym: Perfect passive participle of prōvehō.

From Proto-Italic *fortis, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰértis (“the act of carrying”) (compare Old Irish brith, German Geburt, English bear, burden, Russian бремя (bremja, “burden”), брать (bratʹ, “to take”), Sanskrit भृति (bhṛti, “carrying”)), derivative of *bʰer-, whence also Latin ferō (“bring, carry”). For the semantic development, compare Proto-Germanic *buriz (“favorable wind”), from the same root.
From in- (“not”) +‎ aequus (“equal, even, fair”).
Present participle of attollō.
Derived from lep(ōs) (“pleasantness”, “sweetness”) +‎ -idus (“tending to”, adjectival suffix).
Diminutive from liber (“book”) +‎ -lus.
Compare typologically Russian семе́чки (seméčki), ещё цвето́чки (ješčó cvetóčki).
Borrowed from Latin perennis.
An alternative theory derives the word from Proto-Indo-European *seh₁- (“to sow”).

vocabList.definition: to prefer, want more or instead
vocabList.etym: From magis +‎ volō, literally "I more greatly wish for".
Present participle of mānō.

vocabList.definition: In vain, vainly, needlessly, uselessly, fruitlessly, pointlessly
bound up, having been bound up, tied together, having been tied together
vocabList.etym: Perfect passive participle of dēligō ("bind up, tie together;  bandage").
From Proto-Italic *oinelos, diminutive of Proto-Italic *oinos (“one”), akin to Latin ūnus, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *óynos.
From quī +‎ -cumque; quīcunque is a later development reflecting the assimilated pronunciation.

vocabList.definition: pond, swamp, fen; any piece of standing water
vocabList.etym: Possibly from a Proto-Indo-European *steh₂g- (“to seep, drip”), whence also Ancient Greek στάζω (stázō, “to drip”) (with different ablaut grade), as well as Old Breton staer (“river, brook”).[1] Conversely, possibly related to Ancient Greek τέναγος (ténagos, “shoal water, shallows”).

vocabList.definition: to devastate, ravage or lay waste
vocabList.etym: From vāstus +‎ -ō.
Perfect passive participle of solvō
From re- +‎ pōnō (“put”).

vocabList.definition: gradually, little by little, bit by bit
vocabList.etym: From paulus (“little”) +‎ -ātim (adverb-forming suffix).
From clausus (“shut, closed”), perfect passive participle of claudō (“I shut, close”).

From Proto-Italic *leɣʷis (with possible contamination from *breɣʷis), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁lengʰwih₂-, from *h₁léngʰus, from *h₁lengʷʰ- (“lightweight”). Cognates include Sanskrit लघु (laghú), Ancient Greek ἐλᾰφρός, ἐλᾰχῠ́ς (elăphrós, elăkhŭ́s) and Old English lēoht (English light).
Perfect passive participle of impendō (“weigh out, expend”).
Probably from a Proto-Indo-European *h₂esp- (“to cut”), also present in Ancient Greek ἀσπίς (aspís, “shield”) and Hittite [script needed] (ḫasp-, “to cut down”).[1]
From Proto-Indo-European *deywós, the same source as deus (“god”) and dīvus (“divine”). Originally meaning "favored by the gods, blessed, divine".

vocabList.definition: to cultivate the land, till, tend, take care of a field or garden (literal)
vocabList.etym: Cognates include Ancient Greek πέλω (pélō), πόλος (pólos), τέλλω (téllō), τέλος (télos), τῆλε (têle), πάλαι (pálai), κύκλος (kúklos), Sanskrit चरति (cárati), English wheel.
From Proto-Finnic *lat'ëk, borrowed from Proto-Norse *ᚠᛚᚨᛏᛃᚨ (*flatja), from Proto-Germanic *flatją. Cognates include Finnish lattia and Karelian late.
Reduplication of  quam. The original meaning was hypothetically “how(much)ever”; compare quisquis (“whoever”).

vocabList.definition:
to take away, take off, bear away, bear off, carry off, remove, withdraw
  to bear or carry away, sweep away by wings, the winds, waves, or any other quick motion; waft away, sweep away
 to take away, carry off, etc.

 to mislead, deceive
vocabList.etym: From au- (“from, away, off”) +‎ ferō (“to bear, carry, bring”). Whether the prefix au- is identical to ab- is the source of much controversy; see au- for more.
Traditionally derived from Proto-Indo-European *pel- (“flour, dust”), with accompanying comparanda given in the box below.

Analyzable as con- +‎ *fes +‎ -tim, built on the same root as the verb festīnō (“to hasten”). De Vaan, citing Schrijver, identifies the root as *bʰris-, alleged to also be the source of Welsh brys (“speed, haste”). If this etymology is correct, the Latin form developed a syllabic resonant (*-r〭-) which was then replaced with *-er-, and the resulting cluster *-rst- was then regularly simplified to -st- (compare testis). The ending comes from the adverbial accusative of a deverbal noun, which De Vaan reconstructs as Proto-Indo-European *bʰristi-, Proto-Italic *fristi- (“haste”).[1]

vocabList.definition:
an indirect, roundabout path; a wandering to and fro, twists and turns
Used to denote any intricate or tortuous process, system or scheme
vocabList.etym: From ambi- (“around”) +‎ agō (“to behave, proceed”) +‎ -ēs (noun-forming suffix).
Contracted form of dīves.
From germen (“sprout, bud”), perhaps for *germ(i)nānus.[1] Not to be confused with the unrelated Germānus.
Perfect passive participle of dīligō (“I esteem, love, select”).
in- (“un-”) +‎  Old Latin mānis (“good”), related to māne (“early in the morning”) and mānēs (“benevolent spirits of the departed”), from Proto-Indo-European *meh₂- (“timely, opportune”).
From in- +‎ pius.

vocabList.definition: eagerly, joyfully, with relish or alacrity
vocabList.etym: alacer +‎ -ter
From vigil.

vocabList.definition: plunder, booty, pillage, spoils of war, property taken in war
vocabList.etym: Likely from the o-grade Proto-Italic *praiɣodā, from (with the prefix *prai-) Proto-Indo-European *gʰed-, whence also the second element in prehendō and probably also hedera.[1]
pellō +‎ -sus (action noun)

vocabList.definition: long, a long while, a while, for long, for a long time
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *djous, from Proto-Indo-European *dyéw(i) (“during the day”), locative case of *dyḗws, with d possibly imported from diēs. Cognate with Old Armenian տիւ (tiw), Sanskrit दिवा (divā, “by day”).
Perfect passive participle of dēcernō.
From summa +‎ -ātim.

vocabList.definition: to exhibit, make public, show clearly
vocabList.etym: From manifestus (“apparent, palpable, manifest”) +‎ -ō.
From fūcus (“seaweed, orchil, pretense”) +‎ -ō.

From Proto-Italic *weneznom (“lust, desire”), from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to strive, wish, love”). See also Sanskrit वनति (vanati, “gain, wish, erotic lust”), Latin Venus, veneror, venia, vēnor and English wish.

vocabList.definition: to hide, conceal, keep secret, cover, suppress, sheathe
vocabList.etym: From ab- (“away”) +‎ -dō (“put”).
From octō (“eight”) + centum (“hundred”). Influenced by septingentī.
Perfect active participle of cōnspicor (“see, observe, notice”).
Of Celtic origin, from Gaulish asseda, from Proto-Celtic *eks-dī-sedo-, the root of which is from Proto-Indo-European *sed- (“sit”); cognate with Old Breton assedam.

vocabList.definition: to crowd or press together, compress
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Indo-European *steyp- (“to be stiff, erect”). Cognate with stīpes (“tree trunk, stick”), stips (“small donation, alms”); outside of Latin, compare Proto-Germanic *stīfaz (“stiff”), Lithuanian sti̇̀pti (“to stiffen”).[1]
From dis- (“assunder, apart, utterly”) +‎ tendō (“stretch”).
From mel (“honey”).
From in- +‎ (g)nāvus.
From praesaepiō (“barricade, fence in”).

vocabList.definition: to emit a scent or odor
vocabList.etym: From red- +‎ oleō (“smell”).
From Proto-Italic *farstjagjom, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰérstis, from *bʰers- (“tip”). Compare Middle Irish brostaim (“I goad, spur”), English bristle, Polish barszcz (“hogweed”).

From earlier eira (Plautus), from Proto-Italic *eizā, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁eys- (compare Ancient Greek οἶστρος (oîstros), Lithuanian aistrà (“violent passion”), Avestan 𐬀𐬉𐬴𐬨𐬀 (aēṣ̌ma, “anger”)).
Perfect passive participle of summittō.
Perfect passive participle of collocō.
From per- +‎ exig(ō) (“to demand”) +‎ -uus.
Perfect passive participle of intermittō.
From Old Latin im, em (“then, there”), from is (compare quum, tum), and the demonstrative suffix *-de.

vocabList.definition: soft, smooth, gentle, moderate, mild, calm
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *lēnis (“soft, mild”), from Proto-Indo-European *leh₁- (“lazy, slow; soft”).[1]

May be from Proto-Indo-European *ksew-, extended from *kes- (“to scratch, itch”). Cognates with novācula, sentis, Ancient Greek ξέω (xéō), ξύω (xúō, “to scrape”), ξαίνω (xaínō), Old English besnyþian.
From caecus +‎ -ō.
From Proto-Italic *karpō, from Proto-Indo-European *kerp-.

vocabList.definition: to be favorable, to be well disposed or inclined towards, to favor, promote, befriend, countenance, protect
vocabList.etym: Uncertain. Possibly from Proto-Indo-European *bʰuH- (“to be, become”) via a stative *bʰh₂weh₁yeti (“to be favorable to”)[1] (> *fawēō) or a causative *bʰowh₂eyeti[2] (> *foweō). Alternatively, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰew- (cognate with Proto-Slavic *gověti) via *gʷʰoweti > *foweō.[2] The latter two derivations would be examples of unrounding of *o before *w.
From Proto-Italic *pāskō, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂- (“to protect, shepherd”). Compare Ancient Greek ποιμαίνω (poimaínō, “to tend, feed, nourish”).
From quī +‎ -cumque; quīcunque is a later development reflecting the assimilated pronunciation.

vocabList.definition: to touch on all sides, take hold of, come into contact with
vocabList.etym: From con- (“together”) +‎ tangō (“touch”).
From Proto-Italic *kʷoizā, from Proto-Indo-European *kʷeys- (“to heed”).

vocabList.definition: to bear, bring, drive, or carry back, off, or away
vocabList.etym: From re- +‎ ferō (“bear, carry”).

vocabList.definition: to approve wholly of something; to assent to, sanction,  acknowledge
vocabList.etym: From con- (“completely”) +‎ probō (“to esteem as good, serviceable, fit, just”).
From rapiō (“snatch”) +‎ -idus.[1]

vocabList.definition: to murmur, mutter, grumble, growl at or after something
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *fremō, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrém-e-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrem-. Cognates include Ancient Greek βρέμω (brémō), Middle High German bremen, Welsh brefu,[1] and obsolete English breme (“famous; tempestuous”).
From a Proto-Indo-European collocative compound *h₂yu-gʷih₃- (“long life”). Cognate to Ancient Greek ὑγιής (hugiḗs, “healthy”), Avestan 𐬫𐬀𐬎𐬎𐬀𐬈-𐬘𐬍 (yauuae-jī), Proto-Germanic *aiwukiz. Contrast iugus.

vocabList.definition: hair of the head, lock of hair, plume
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *kriznis, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ker- (“to turn, bend”). Cognate with Latin crista, crispus (“curly”) and Albanian krip.

vocabList.definition: to have or put forth leaves; to be in leaf, become green
vocabList.etym: From frōns (“leaves”).

vocabList.definition: to sound, resound, make a sound or noise (and various sounds in-context)
vocabList.etym: See the etymology of the corresponding lemma form.
From Proto-Indo-European *h₃émsos (“shoulder”) by rhotacism and vowel anaptyxis -ms- > -mer-. Cognates include Ancient Greek ὦμος (ômos), Sanskrit अंस (áṃsa), and Gothic 𐌰𐌼𐍃 (ams).

vocabList.definition: to shine forth or out, gleam; brighten
vocabList.etym: From ex- (“out of”) +‎ niteō (“shine”).

vocabList.definition: bog, morass, place where boars and swine wallow
vocabList.etym: Per De Vaan (2008), from Proto-Indo-European *l(H)u-(s)tro- (“dirty place”), from Proto-Indo-European *le(H)w- (the same root as lutum (“mud, dirt, clay”)).[1] Valpy (1828) proposed instead a borrowing, with change of *d to /l/, from Ancient Greek *δύστρον (*dústron), from δύω (dúō, “to plunge”).[2]
From dēiciō (“I cast away, I throw [down]”).
From caper (“billy goat, he-goat”) +‎ -a (suffix forming feminine versions of nouns).[1]

vocabList.definition: dusty, pulverulent, full of dust, dust-raising, resembling a cloud of dust
vocabList.etym: From pulvis (“dust”) +‎ -ulentus (“full of, abounding in”).

vocabList.definition: to glomerate, make into a ball, pile in a heap
vocabList.etym: From glomus, glomeris (“a roughly spherical mass”) +‎ -ō.
From ne- + Proto-Indo-European *meh₁- (whence metior). Compare immēnsus from these roots.
From sub (“under”) +‎ dolus (“deceit”).
From dissimulō (“dissemble, conceal”) +‎ -tor.

vocabList.definition: to be pleasing; to be agreeable
vocabList.etym: From lubet, from Proto-Italic *luβēt, from Proto-Indo-European stative *lubʰ-eh₁-(ye)-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *lewbʰ- (“to love, care for, desire”). Cognate with English love, lief, German lieben, Liebe, Russian любить (ljubitʹ), Sanskrit लुभ्यति (lubhyati).
From rapiō.

vocabList.definition: the act of cutting or lopping something off
vocabList.etym: From caedō (“to cut down, hew”) +‎ -ēs.

From Proto-Italic *ferōks, from earlier *xʷerōks, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰweroh₃kʷs (“having the appearance of a wild animal”), from *ǵʰwero- (early Proto-Italic *xʷeros, suffixed form *ǵʰwer- (“wild animal”)) + *h₃ekʷ- (“eye; to see”).
From inops (“helpless, destitute, poor”) +‎ -ia.

From Proto-Italic *prāwos (whence also Faliscan 𐌐𐌓𐌀𐌖𐌉𐌏𐌔 (prauios, praenomen)). Further etymology unknown.[1][2] Pokorny's derivation from Proto-Indo-European *preh₂-wo-s, from *preh₂- (“to bend”), whence also prātum, is nowadays rejected.
in- +‎ edō (“to eat”) +‎ -ia
From algeō (“I am, feel cold”) +‎ -or.
Passive perfect participle of prŏfundō.
Adverbial accusative of  parvus. Doublet of  parvum.
Present active participle of ārdeō (“burn”).
From in- (“in, into”) +‎ vādō (“to go, rush”).

vocabList.definition: allotment, portion, weight (of wool measured out to a slave to spin in a day)
vocabList.etym: Neuter of past participle of pendō.

vocabList.definition: to follow someone in order to come up to him; pursue, go after
vocabList.etym: From ad- +‎ sequor (“follow”).

vocabList.definition: to increase, augment, enlarge, spread, expand
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *augeō, from earlier *augejō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂owg-éye-ti, causative form of *h₂ewg-.
From Proto-Indo-European *gʷegs-, from Proto-Indo-European *gʷog- (“to shake, swing”). Cognate with Old English cweccan (“to shake, swing, move, vibrate; shake off, give up”). More at quake.
From Proto-Italic *tegō, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)teg- (“to cover with a roof”). Cognate with English thatch and English deck.

vocabList.definition: fortified, having been fortified; secured, having been secured; protected, having been protected
vocabList.etym: Perfect passive participle of mūniō (“fortify”).
From contendō +‎ -tiō.

vocabList.definition: to make wider, widen, extend, enlarge, increase, amplify, augment, magnify
vocabList.etym: amplus (“large, wide, ample”) +‎ -iō (suffix creating causative verbs).
Perfect passive participle of dēpōnō.
Future active participle of faciō.
From por- +‎ liceor.

vocabList.definition: to find, find out, learn, realise, ascertain, discover, invent
vocabList.etym: From re- +‎ pariō (“to give birth”), from Proto-Indo-European *perh₃- (“to produce, beget”).
From con- (“with, together”) +‎ tendō (“stretch, extend; contend”).
Univerbation of paulīs (“a few, a little”, abl. pl.) +‎ -per (“through”), originally a postpositional phrase.

vocabList.definition: town (esp. of towns other than Rome, which was generally called Urbs)
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *oppedom, from Proto-Indo-European *pedo- meaning either "step > ground" or "foot"  - compare the morphology of Ancient Greek ἐπίπεδος (epípedos, “plane, superficial”). Cognates include Ancient Greek πέδον (pédon), Sanskrit पद (pada, “on or over the plain”).
Perfect passive participle of comprehendō.

vocabList.definition: swamp, marsh, morass, bog, fen, pool
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *palūts, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *pelH- (“pale, gray”), presumably with semantic shift "gray" > "swamp", though this is semantically tenuous. Either way, related to Latvian peļķe (“puddle”), Lithuanian pelkė (“marsh”), Sanskrit पल्वल (palvala, “pool, pond”), and possibly Ancient Greek πηλός (pēlós, “mud, earth, clay”).[1]
Perfect participle of moror.

vocabList.definition: (zoology) A group of large domestic animals: a herd of cattle, horses, or donkeys; such animals in a collective sense: cattle and equines.
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *pekos, from Proto-Indo-European *péḱ-os (“livestock”). Related to pecū, from Proto-Indo-European *peḱu- (“livestock, domestic animals”). Cognates include Sanskrit पशु (páśu, “cattle”), Old Armenian ասր (asr, “fleece”), Old Saxon fehu, Old English feoh, Gothic 𐍆𐌰𐌹𐌷𐌿 (faihu), Old Norse fé, Swedish fä and Lithuanian pēkus (“cattle”).
Perfect passive participle of cōgō (“force, compel”).
From ad- +‎ orior.
From in- +‎ prōvīsus.

vocabList.definition: to lead, draw, bring or conduct back; bring or accompany home
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Italic *wredoukō. Equivalent to re- (“back, again”) +‎ dūcō (“lead”).
From in- (“un-”) +‎  unattested *calamis ("damaged"). See calamitas.[1]
Perfect passive participle of permoveō.
See repēns (“sudden, unexpected”).

From *vectīgum  +‎ -ālis, from Proto-Indo-European *wektih₂ǵom (“fee for vehicle-driving”), synchronically analyzable as vectis +‎ agō +‎ um. When this noun was compounded, vectis had a different meaning than it has in classical Latin.
From Proto-Italic *pendō, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)pénd-e-ti, from *(s)pend- (“to pull; to spin”). Related to pendeō, pondus.[1]
From dēdō (“to give away, to give up”) +‎ -tiō (noun-forming suffix).

vocabList.definition: to expose to view, exhibit, show
vocabList.etym: For *obstendō, from obs- + tendō. Compare obtendō.
From incolō (“to inhabit, dwell in”) +‎ -a (agent noun), from in + colō (“dwell, inhabit”).
From properus (“hasty”) +‎ -ē (adverbial ending).
From in- +‎ pendeō (“to be suspended, hang”).

vocabList.definition: deception, deceit, fraud, guile, treachery, trickery
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Indo-European *dolh₁os. Cognate to Oscan [script needed] (dolom, “intention, ruse”) and Ancient Greek δόλος (dólos),[1] but the Italic terms may be borrowings from the latter.
From ē- +‎ nūntiō
Adverb from *frusterus, for *frudterus/ *fruditerus, from fraus (“harm, injury”).[1]
From sub- +‎ capiō (“seize”).

vocabList.definition: to consult, seek counsel from, take counsel from
vocabList.etym: con- +‎ *sulo, a derivation of Proto-Indo-European *selh₁- (“to take, grab”).[1] Compare with cōnsul and cōnsilium. Cognate with English sell, sale.

vocabList.definition: any double-doored entrance (e.g. a domestic door or a gate to a temple or city)
vocabList.etym: From Proto-Indo-European *yeh₂- (“to go, go in, travel”). Cognate with Old Church Slavonic ꙗдо (jado, “to travel”) and Sanskrit यान (yāna, “path”).

vocabList.definition: to dig (thoroughly), dig up or over, dig round about, turn over (of land), prepare by digging
vocabList.etym: From con- (“with, together”) +‎ fodiō (“dig; thrust, stab”).
From im- (“without, not”) + paratus (“prepared, ready”).

vocabList.definition: time free from activity: leisure, free time
vocabList.etym: Uncertain;[1] perhaps from Proto-Italic *autiom, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ewtyom (“forlorn, deserted”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ew (“off, away from”).
Univerbation of et (“and, also”) +‎ iam (“now, already”).
Present active participle of surgō (“[I] get up, arise”).

vocabList.definition: to look behind, look back at or upon, look to, look around
vocabList.etym: From re- (“back; again”) +‎ speciō (“observe, look at”).

From Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰeh₁ro- (“derelict”), from the root *ǵʰeh₁- (“to leave behind, abandon”). Cognate with Ancient Greek χήρα (khḗra, “widow”). (This etymology is missing or incomplete. Please add to it, or discuss it at the Etymology scriptorium. Particularly: “-ēd-?”)
From Proto-Italic *telnos, perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *telnos ~ *telnes-, from *telh₂- (“flat ground”), but reshaped after rūs. Otherwise, could derive from Etruscan 𐌕𐌖𐌋𐌀𐌓 (tular, “earth”).
From the root of celer, from Proto-Indo-European *kel- (“to drive, force to move quickly”).

vocabList.definition:
(of textures or forms) thin, slender, slim, lank; especially:


(with anima or umbra) synonym of mānēs, the manes[4]
vocabList.etym: Inherited from Proto-Indo-European *ténh₂us (“thin”).[1][2][3] Original u-stem adjectives are regularly extended into i-stem ones in Latin, compare gravis, brevis, dulcis, etc.
From ex- (“out of”) +‎ vānēscō (“disappear”).

vocabList.definition: to lose one's speech, become dumb
vocabList.etym: From ob- +‎ mūtus +‎ -ēscō.
From ā- (prefix denoting absence) +‎ mēns (“mind, reason”).

vocabList.definition: looked at, beheld, having been looked at
vocabList.etym: Perfect passive participle of aspiciō (“behold, see; catch sight of”).

vocabList.definition: perfect passive participle of arrigō: erect, perpendicular, upright; (rare) steep, precipitous
vocabList.etym: From arrigō (“I set up, erect”).
Borrowed from Ancient Greek κόμη (kómē, “hair of the head”). For sense 2, compare crīniō (“to cover with leaves, or hair”).

vocabList.definition: to stick, stick fast; cling; cleave; adhere; hang, hang on or to; hold fast, be fastened; hang on; be caught; take root
(literal) the upper part of a throat; a throat, pharynx, gullet
vocabList.etym: Plural of faux, of unknown etymology.[1]

From ār(i)dus +‎ -eō. Cf. audeō < avidus. For the supine ārsum compare also audeō : ausum and gaudeō : gavīsum, in which the i was retained. It is possible that this term is cognate with Umbrian aso, the perfect passive participle of an unattested verb which may have been the Umbrian equivalent of this term.

vocabList.definition:
to depart, go away, go off, exit


 to pass away

to retire from office

 to set
vocabList.etym: From ab- (“from, away”) +‎ eō (“go”).
Perfect passive participle of attonō.
Perfect passive participle of moneō (“warn, remind”).

vocabList.definition: to speak to, address, accost, implore
vocabList.etym: From ad- +‎ for (“speak, say”).
From Proto-Indo-European *terh₁- (“to rub, rub by twisting, twist, turn”).

vocabList.definition: time free from activity: leisure, free time
vocabList.etym: Uncertain;[1] perhaps from Proto-Italic *autiom, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ewtyom (“forlorn, deserted”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ew (“off, away from”).
ambi- (“around”) +‎ eō (“go”)
From exōrdior.

vocabList.definition: to take, take up, catch, assume, seize, claim, arrogate
vocabList.etym: Ultimately from Proto-Italic *emō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁em-. By surface analysis, sub +‎ emō (“to buy, take”), with excrescent p in sūmpsī and sūmptum. According to Sihler, the term derives from earlier *susmō, from Proto-Italic *sups-(e)mō, from *emō.[1][2] It is likely that this Latin term is related to Umbrian sumtu, although Buck argues that the Umbrian term cannot be explained form *sups-(e)mō.[3] Instead, Buck suggests that the Umbrian term must derive from *sup(e)mō, which—according to Poultney—is the source for both the Umbrian and the Latin term.[4] According to De Vaan, the perfect form sūmpsī is a later innovation that emerged because the term was no longer synchronically identifiable with emō.[5] Sextus Pompeius Festus provides attestation for two additional perfect forms surēmi and surēmpsī. De Vaan suggests that these forms may derive from earlier Proto-Italic *suz-ēm-, itself from earlier *subs-ēm-. Alternatively, De Vaan suggests that these terms were remodeled after verbs such as suscipiō.
From Proto-Indo-European *kel- (“to drive”). Probably cognate with Ancient Greek κέλλω (kéllō), Ancient Greek κέλης (kélēs).

vocabList.definition: to this, to this, tothis subject/matter
vocabList.etym: Probably from the Old Latin locative hoi + -ce, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰe and Proto-Indo-European *ḱe (“here”), according to De Vaan (2008). Compare the mostly pre-Classical hōc (“to this place, for this reason”), which De Vaan says is from an instrumental case form.

vocabList.definition: to turn often, keep turning, handle, whirl about, turn over
vocabList.etym: Frequentative verb of vertō.
Present participle of furō.

vocabList.definition: if only!, I wish that!, oh that!, would that!, would to heaven!
vocabList.etym: From ut +‎ -nam.
From Ancient Greek θησαυρός (thēsaurós, “storehouse, treasure”).

vocabList.definition: to conceal, hide, or dissimulate a state of mind
vocabList.etym: From dissimilis (“unlike”) +‎ -ō, with i changed to u before a thick l.

vocabList.definition: to withdraw, retire, depart, leave or go away
vocabList.etym: From dē- +‎ cēdō.
From mōlēs (“a pile, heap”).

vocabList.definition: to sit down, to seat oneself, to settle

vocabList.etym: Substantivized neuter of arvus.

vocabList.definition: Of that which belongs to another person, place, or object—of another, alien, foreign
vocabList.etym: From alius (“other, another”) +‎ -ēnus.
From aequus (“flat, horizontal”).
Perfect passive participle of ignōscō. Compare Ancient Greek ἄγνωτος (ágnōtos).

vocabList.definition: to extract, take out, draw out, pull off
vocabList.etym: From ex- +‎ *uō. Akin to Proto-Slavic *jьzuti.
From Proto-Italic *preks, from Proto-Indo-European *preḱ- (“to request, ask”).
From Proto-Italic *merēō, from earlier *merējō, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)mr̥-éh₁-yeti, from *(s)mer- (“to assign, allot”).
From quis +‎ -quam (“any”). Compare to quisque.
Present participle of lābor.
From sīc +‎ -ne (“focusing particle”).
Present participle of perūrō.

vocabList.definition: to creep under or along, to come upon unawares
vocabList.etym: From sub- +‎ rēpō.
From crūdus.

From Proto-Italic *weneznom (“lust, desire”), from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to strive, wish, love”). See also Sanskrit वनति (vanati, “gain, wish, erotic lust”), Latin Venus, veneror, venia, vēnor and English wish.
